his companions became a set piece in the popular press. Loving Faster than Light focuses on the popular reception of relativity in Britain, demonstrating how abstract science came to be entangled with class politics, new media technology, changing sex relations, crime, cricket, and cinematography in the British imagination during the 1920s. Blending literary analysis with insights from the history of science, Katy Price reveals how cultural meanings for Einstein’s relativity were negotiated in newspapers with differing political agendas, popular science magazines, pulp fiction adventure and romance stories, detective plots, and esoteric love poetry. Loving Faster than Light is an essential read for anyone interested in popular science, the intersection of science and literature, and the social and cultural history of physics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and science. 0aPulp literature, Englishy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRelativityxPress coverage. 0aRelativity. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aromantic, romance, love, einstein, theory, relativity, progress, science, scientist, scientific, academic, scholarly, educational, social, political, economic, culture, cultural, pastiche, britain, parody, history, historical, satire, jokes, newspaper, journalism, new, class, classism, politics, british, immigrant, immigration, 1920s, literary, analysis, stories, poems.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022668073640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226680750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226680750/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d20